org.zeldorblat.lib.result

Interface Result<T,E>

  • Type Parameters:
    T - the class of the encapsulated value
    E - the class of the encapsulated error
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    Result.AbstractResult, Result.FailureResult, Result.SuccessResult

    public interface Result<T,E>
    A monad representing a result that is in exactly one of two states: success or failure. A success Result encapsulates a single (possibly null) Object of class T, and a failure Result encapsulates a single, non-null Object of class E representing an error.

    The monad itself is immutable to the extent that the encapsulated value or error is also immutable.

    Implementing classes need only define the fold() method as all other methods can be derived from its implementation. Implementers may choose to override additional methods as desired, but are responsible for ensuring the immutability requirement.

    The Result interface contains two concrete inner static classes: Result.SuccessResult and Result.FailureResult. It is certainly possible to create other implementations of the Result interface; in practice, however, usages of Result are generally expected to rely on the implementation here. Obtaining new instances of Result should (almost) always be done using the success() and failure() static factory methods.

        <R> R fold(Function<? super T,? extends R> successMapper,
           Function<? super E,? extends R> failureMapper)
        If success, apply successMapper to the encapsulated value and return the answer. If failure, apply failureMapper to the encapsulated error and return the answer.

        Implementing classes need only define this method as all other methods can be derived from the implementation of fold(). Implementers may choose to override additional methods as desired.

        Type Parameters:

        Parameters:

        failureMapper - transform to apply to the encapsulated error
        Returns:
        the result of successMapper or failureMapper
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if successMapper is null or failureMapper is null

      • require

        default Result<T,Object> require(Predicate<? super T> predicate)
        If success, test predicate on the encapsulated value and, if true, return a new success Result containing the original encapsulated value, otherwise return a new failure Result containing a generic error. If failure, cast the encapsulated error to Object and return a new failure Result containing the answer.

        This variant of require() is typically used when only the state of the Result (e.g. success or failure) is significant and the specific error is irrelevant.

        Although the encapsulated error Object is guaranteed to be non-null, implementers should not make assumptions about what this Object actually is.

        Parameters:
        predicate - test to apply to the encapsulated value
        Returns:
        the Result
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if predicate is null
        See Also:
        require(Predicate, Function), failIf(Predicate)

        This variant of fail() is typically used when only the state of the Result (e.g. success or failure) is significant and the specific error is irrelevant.

        Although the encapsulated error Object is guaranteed to be non-null, implementers should not make assumptions about what this Object actually is.
